## ⚠️ Production Mode Matters (Webpack Example)

```js
// webpack.config.js
mode: "production"
```

✅ Enables tree shaking + minification  
❌ In `development` mode, tree shaking may not run

***

## ✅ Side Effects: A Critical Concept (Interview Favorite 🔥)

Tree shaking removes code **only if it’s safe** to remove.

### ✅ Safe (No Side Effects)

```js
export const PI = 3.14;
```

### ❌ Unsafe (Has Side Effects)

```js
console.log("Running module");
```

This code **must stay**, even if exports aren’t used.

***

### ✅ `sideEffects` Flag (package.json)

```json
{
  "sideEffects": false
}
```

✅ Tells bundler it’s safe to remove unused files  
✅ Improves tree shaking significantly

Or selectively:

```json
{
  "sideEffects": ["*.css"]
}
```

***

## ✅ Tree Shaking in Real Libraries

Modern libraries ship **ESM builds** to support tree shaking.

### ✅ Good

```js
import { debounce } from "lodash-es";
```

### ❌ Bad

```js
import _ from "lodash";
```

✅ Only needed code is included  
❌ Entire library is bundled

***

## ✅ Tree Shaking in React Apps

```js
import { useState } from "react";
```

✅ Only `useState` is included  
✅ Other React APIs are excluded if unused

This is why **named imports matter**.

***

## ✅ What Tree Shaking Is NOT

❌ Not a runtime feature  
❌ Not the same as minification  
❌ Not effective with dynamic imports like:

```js
import(moduleName);
```

***

## ⚠️ Common Limitations

*   ❌ Dynamic imports & dynamic requires
*   ❌ Side‑effect‑heavy modules
*   ❌ CommonJS modules
*   ❌ Mutating exports

***

## ✅ Tree Shaking vs Minification

| Feature             | Tree Shaking | Minification |
| ------------------- | ------------ | ------------ |
| Removes unused code | ✅ Yes        | ❌ No         |
| Shrinks code size   | ✅ Yes        | ✅ Yes        |
| When it runs        | Build time   | Build time   |
| Example tool        | Rollup       | Terser       |

✅ Usually used **together**

***

## ✅ One‑Line Interview Answer

> Tree shaking is a build‑time optimization that removes unused code from JavaScript bundles using static analysis of ES module imports and exports.

***

## ✅ 10‑Second Interview Explanation

> Tree shaking works with ES modules to eliminate unused exports so that only the code actually used in the application is bundled.

***

## ✅ Best Practices to Enable Tree Shaking

✅ Use `import` / `export`  
✅ Avoid `require()`  
✅ Use named imports  
✅ Set `mode: "production"`  
✅ Mark `sideEffects: false` where safe

